column103: The Spotted Deer has a bright golden-brown body with white spots extending from the legs to the neck. Males are darker, larger, and have black facial markings. The underparts are white or creamy, and the short tail and strong legs support its agile build. Only males have antlers, which are brown, smooth, and slender, typically 50–80 cm long with three tines per side. Adults measure 90–140 cm in body length, with a tail of 10–25 cm, stand 70–90 cm at the shoulder, and weigh 35–85 kg. The number of tines may vary based on the animal’s condition.

column103: The hedgehog is a medium-sized, compact animal (25–30 cm) with a short tail, dense pale or light brown spines for defense, and a small pointed head with a distinct snout. It has well-furred, prominent ears for thermoregulation, small side-positioned eyes for low-light vision, and short, sturdy legs with five-toed feet suited for digging. Its body is light brown or beige with darker-tipped spines, a pale underside, and soft, light-colored skin beneath the spines.

column103: Wild boars range from 153 to 240 cm in total length and weigh 66 to 272 kg as adults. They have a short muzzle, with the snout disc perpendicular to the axis of the head. They have no facial warts and large ears. The fur is brown, tinged with black and grey hairs, and a stiff mane of "hog bristles" along the back. The face, cheeks, and throat have whitish markings. The legs are long and narrow, with the medial false hooves being long. Males grow relatively large, visible upper tusks. Four to six pairs of mammae.

column103: Cuvier's beaked whale has a V-shaped pair of throat grooves, characteristic of beaked whales, is present. The flippers are small, and the high dorsal fin may be sickle-shaped or triangular. The rear margin of the flukes is slightly concave. Colouration varies between individuals, with the back being dark rust brown, slate grey, or fawn-coloured, while the belly is usually lighter. The head, especially in older males, is paler and almost completely white. Linear light scars are commonly found on the back and sides, along with white or cream-coloured oval blotches on the belly and sides. Juveniles tend to be lighter than their parents. The head and body length ranges from 500 to 700 cm.

column103: The common dolphin is one of the easiest dolphins to identify as it has a characteristic hourglass pattern on its body across the flanks. The back always darker, can be brownish, black or purplish, with a yellow or tan patch on both sides. Its undersides are white or creamy, there is a darker circle around its eyes and a dark stripe from flipper or jaw. Its has broad, black flippers and its dorsal fin is tall with a pointed tip. It has 80-120 teeth in each jay. The body size is 2-2.5 meter and weight is up to 240 kg.

column103: The Indian flying fox or Indian flying bat has a chestnut-brown head with large black, pointed ears and huge black wings that often fold over a tan or orange belly. The back is blackish brown with scattered pale hair. On folded wings, the rich colouration of the body can be fully covered. Making the bat look black, it has a long, hairy snout with visible nostrils.
